I'm 40 years old, have been interested in computers my entire life. Started simple, with some LOGO and BASIC when I was in Grade 6, at 12 years old, as part of mandatory class work. I learned a little more in high school, took Comp Sci 11 when I was in Grade 10, and finished Comp Sci 12 in Grade 12 learning Turbo Pascal. Developed my first game as a class project, and presented it to the school Principal. And that is where I stopped. Big mistake. I've done "jobs". Not programming jobs...just regular jobs. Jobs I pretty much always hated and got bored of quickly. McDonalds. Tim Horton's. Temporary labour jobs. Office jobs. Call center jobs. But nothing ever stuck until recently, I actually held down a job for 2 years. Maybe I grew up? But as expected...eventually, i got bored, as well as sick, because it wasn't the healthiest environment. For the first time...I felt satisfaction, I enjoyed what I did, enjoyed the corporation, the people I worked with. But i still struggled to maintain my interest after the 1st year, and it showed. My attendance slipped. I still worked hard...when I was there!

But eventually, they were forced to let me go. No hard feelings. I understood. I went into a depression. Spent much of my time gaming... and it hit me. At 40 years old, I'm still interested in gaming? And technology? Why don't I DO something about it? I applied for EI (still waiting), and decided...in the meantime... why don't I spend the time that I was gaming... learning? So... here I am. A beginner, since all that language knowledge of over 20 years ago is obsolete. I hope however, some of the lessons about the FUNDAMENTALS of programming stuck, even if the languages themselves won't benefit me at this stage.

1981 | Computer 1: Texas Ti994/A

Later: c128 - Amiga… And then 1986. Macintosh Plus (even if the Amiga was cooler for a couple of years ahead).

The difference now from back in the days, was that to do something you learned about how things worked. Of course we where dreaming of the future (a pixel digitzied photo on C64 by Triad if i remember it correctly, was amazing back then!), where things was easy. No CLI, and no tuning the cassette player to load data correctly (if you played music on your stereo, some data would fail to load).

But now, the CLI is fun again. I got no Unix Beard, and my line of work is not coding (Graphic Artist). However, i want to learn things. Instead of buying a expensive license of some poorly done GUI app to do certain things, i mostly ending up doing myself with ”remixing” Open Source Code and doing BASH scripts or using Automator (with Shell Scripts).

Also i'm extremly greatful for all the people using Open Source Licenses for others to study, learn and use. I hate when Large (and small) corporations using Open Source Code and don't respect the Licenses, which seems to be more common.

So, that's the Unix Beard part. The rest of the story you can read in my memoirs (kidding!). Cheers!
